WEBVTT



00:00:00.576 --> 00:00:04.608
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:00:04.352 --> 00:00:09.824
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization.

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:18.784
using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:00:18.848 --> 00:00:27.040
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:00:27.008 --> 00:00:36.448
Today, we invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:00:38.752 --> 00:00:48.032
Peace be with you. Friends, for this 25th Sunday of Ordinary Time, I want to focus not on the Gospel. I preached on it many times before the great parable of the...

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:55.616
The unjust steward, which is very rich, but I want to focus on readings two and one, because when read together, I think.

00:00:55.392 --> 00:00:57.760
They give us a very good sense of, you know,

00:00:57.568 --> 00:01:01.216
Catholic social teaching in regard to the question of

00:01:01.088 --> 00:01:02.240
Power.

00:01:02.112 --> 00:01:04.096
Of political power.

00:01:03.904 --> 00:01:11.136
The church's position is a subtle one, and I think much of the conversation today kind of breaks on either side of it.

00:01:10.944 --> 00:01:12.352
And the church...

00:01:12.128 --> 00:01:17.056
typically gives this sort of both and answer. I think you see the roots of it.

00:01:16.768 --> 00:01:20.192
in these two texts the church gives us.

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:22.144
Let me first observe this.

00:01:22.624 --> 00:01:25.088
And I've said this many times before.

00:01:25.568 --> 00:01:31.104
I think the most influential 19th century philosopher on the scene today is

00:01:30.880 --> 00:01:32.480
is Friedrich Nietzsche

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:34.368
More than Karl Marx.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:38.240
Nietzsche, who said everything comes down to plays of power.

00:01:38.368 --> 00:01:46.368
I'm oversimplifying it, of course, but that the fundamental reality is power and the abuse of power, the use of power, right?

00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:47.968
Who has power?

00:01:47.936 --> 00:01:51.104
Who's benefiting from it who's a victim of it

00:01:51.072 --> 00:01:58.976
The tendency, especially today, to divide the world into two camps. There's oppressors who have power and the oppressed who don't have it.

00:01:58.688 --> 00:02:03.328
and their ongoing struggle. Well, that's a very Nietzschean perspective.

00:02:02.912 --> 00:02:10.176
Yeah. Bequeathed to modern times by figures such as Martin Heidegger, Michel Foucault, Ayn Rand. Yeah.

00:02:09.952 --> 00:02:11.328
Many others.

00:02:11.328 --> 00:02:14.368
And I think it's come to dominate.

00:02:14.368 --> 00:02:16.512
It's the mentality of many. So that the...

00:02:16.736 --> 00:02:20.160
There's a tendency to demonize power

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:24.096
You know, when you say, well, look, that group has got power, right?

00:02:24.096 --> 00:02:29.664
Yeah, because they want to oppress others. That guy's got power, and that's not right. Right.

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:32.960
And these people are powerless and that's a problem.

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:35.968
So power tends to be seen as something

00:02:36.032 --> 00:02:38.496
Almost entirely negative

00:02:38.784 --> 00:02:40.960
Well, let me say this bluntly.

00:02:41.376 --> 00:02:43.936
The Bible is not in sympathy.

00:02:43.968 --> 00:02:50.080
with this sort of one-sided Nietzschean Foucauldian demonization of power.

00:02:50.144 --> 00:02:56.896
The Bible does not see the world as divided simply into two camps of oppressors with power and oppressed

00:02:56.640 --> 00:02:58.080
Who don't have power.

00:02:58.336 --> 00:03:00.384
And one of the great texts, I think,

00:03:00.672 --> 00:03:03.520
is the one that's proposed now for our second reading.

00:03:03.392 --> 00:03:05.888
It's from Paul's first letter to...

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:06.784
Timothy.

00:03:07.264 --> 00:03:08.480
Here's what we hear.

00:03:09.248 --> 00:03:11.424
Beloved, first of all, I ask,

00:03:11.712 --> 00:03:14.272
That supplications prayers

00:03:14.176 --> 00:03:17.920
1. Petitions and thanksgivings be offered for everyone. 2.

00:03:18.368 --> 00:03:19.872
For kings

00:03:19.712 --> 00:03:21.504
And for all in authority.

00:03:21.728 --> 00:03:26.368
That we may lead a quiet and tranquil life in all devotion and dignity.

00:03:27.168 --> 00:03:35.392
Well, if Paul thought kings were just corrupt, kings were just the wielders of oppressive power,

00:03:35.136 --> 00:03:38.272
Why would you pray for them? You want to overthrow them.

00:03:38.176 --> 00:03:40.000
You'd want to resist them.

00:03:40.608 --> 00:03:42.496
No, he's saying...

00:03:43.008 --> 00:03:45.888
8.

00:03:45.632 --> 00:03:49.248
For kings and all those in authority.

00:03:49.120 --> 00:03:53.376
Why? That we may lead a quiet and tranquil life. Right.

00:03:53.888 --> 00:03:58.208
What's the purpose of political power? Well, see, don't demonize it.

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:01.792
Because indeed, God is described as all-powerful, all-powerful.

00:04:01.952 --> 00:04:04.992
So power can't in itself be a problem.

00:04:05.568 --> 00:04:07.200
If God has power,

00:04:07.232 --> 00:04:12.928
Well, those who are participating in God, who are imitating God in their use of power,

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:16.768
are doing something that's really good. And namely, we hear it.

00:04:16.544 --> 00:04:26.080
then we may lead a quiet and tranquil life in all devotion and dignity. Not a bad little description of the purpose of government there.

00:04:26.304 --> 00:04:29.888
So there's a kind of basic purpose of, you know, kind of keeping things organized.

00:04:29.696 --> 00:04:32.224
Quiet and peaceful that we might

00:04:32.224 --> 00:04:34.592
lead our lives productively.

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:40.512
economically and in terms of our friendships and relationships. If we're living in chaos,

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:47.392
Well, then we can't flourish as human beings. And so we need people in power that can provide for.

00:04:47.136 --> 00:04:49.440
This tranquility.

00:04:49.568 --> 00:04:51.488
I like to focus on

00:04:51.712 --> 00:04:54.976
In all devotion and dignity

00:04:55.456 --> 00:05:00.192
One of the cornerstones of Catholic social teaching is the dignity of the individual.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.440
What's the government's purpose? I'm going to give it a somewhat American, more modern spin here, but...

00:05:05.344 --> 00:05:09.984
Part of the purpose of government is to guarantee the dignity of citizens.

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:19.232
We speak of human rights and governments instituted to protect those rights, not creating them, but securing and protecting them.

00:05:19.424 --> 00:05:21.856
All right tranquility peace

00:05:22.016 --> 00:05:23.200
Dignity,

00:05:22.976 --> 00:05:25.664
But then listen now as St. Paul goes on.

00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:27.232
Adding another dimension.

00:05:28.448 --> 00:05:30.368
This is good and pleasing.

00:05:30.304 --> 00:05:31.776
To God our Savior.

00:05:31.616 --> 00:05:33.920
We're praying for those in authority. Now, why? Why

00:05:34.240 --> 00:05:37.280
Who wills everyone to be saved?

00:05:37.248 --> 00:05:39.488
And to come to knowledge of the truth

00:05:39.808 --> 00:05:43.904
Well, now he puts it in a very explicitly theological framework.

00:05:44.128 --> 00:05:48.384
What's at least one of the purposes of political authority?

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:52.544
It's to allow for salvation. Meaning, it seems to me, the

00:05:52.288 --> 00:05:58.720
Providing the context and conditions for a flourishing religiosity.

00:05:59.296 --> 00:06:02.656
100%. We'll speak of religious liberty quite correctly. Yeah.

00:06:03.232 --> 00:06:13.280
The free exercise of religion we say in our American context. Well, quite right. That's one of the purposes of government is to allow for religion to flourish.

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:13.728
Flourish.

00:06:13.536 --> 00:06:14.560
And

00:06:14.496 --> 00:06:18.080
So everyone to be saved and to come to knowledge of the truth.

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:25.248
That knowledge might be shared, that there might be the conditions that make real learning possible.

00:06:25.248 --> 00:06:31.296
I think you hear of Thomas Jefferson who would say one of the purposes of government is to provide for education. Education.

00:06:32.192 --> 00:06:39.840
See, beautiful, don't demonize power as though it's just a bad thing, it's just oppressive. No, no, pray, pray.

00:06:39.648 --> 00:06:42.720
For those in authority, for all these reasons.

00:06:42.656 --> 00:06:46.976
That we might have the basic tranquility we need to flourish

00:06:47.008 --> 00:06:48.384
That we might even.

00:06:48.672 --> 00:06:49.664
Uh, uh,

00:06:49.504 --> 00:06:52.128
Be free to worship God properly.

00:06:52.288 --> 00:06:55.936
Though we might have our dignity and rights preserved, those are all...

00:06:55.680 --> 00:07:01.472
It's beautiful and important things, which is why in its social teaching, the church insists that

00:07:01.376 --> 00:07:04.224
That a properly constituted government

00:07:04.128 --> 00:07:07.552
is participating in the authority of God.

00:07:07.776 --> 00:07:14.240
Now again, it's not to say, oh, they're flawless and we should never ask questions about them. No, no, no, no, no. I'll get there.

00:07:14.048 --> 00:07:16.768
We'll get there in this very sermon.

00:07:16.416 --> 00:07:24.192
But it does mean that legitimate political authority participates in the authority by which God governs.

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:25.408
The universe,

00:07:25.696 --> 00:07:30.880
And so, indeed, look, in the Catholic liturgy, we are positively

00:07:31.008 --> 00:07:32.608
Encouraged

00:07:32.768 --> 00:07:36.736
Indeed, required to pray for those in authority.

00:07:37.056 --> 00:07:47.104
You know, when we're putting the petitions together for Mass, the church recommends the first one be for the Pope and for the bishops, those who lead us in the spiritual order. But then the second

00:07:46.624 --> 00:07:47.968
The second prayer is,

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:54.112
And I always follow this when I'm saying, you know, daily Mass. The second prayer should be for those in authority.

00:07:54.112 --> 00:07:59.232
Those in political would pray for the president, for senators and representatives and our governors, etc.

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:00.384
Good.

00:08:00.192 --> 00:08:01.024
Good.

00:08:01.056 --> 00:08:03.136
Power should not be demonized.

00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:05.504
We should recognize the

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:06.880
The practical

00:08:06.784 --> 00:08:09.984
Moral and indeed spiritual purpose

00:08:09.888 --> 00:08:11.264
Of real power.

00:08:11.776 --> 00:08:12.800
Okay.

00:08:13.056 --> 00:08:20.448
There's part one of Catholic social teaching reflected clearly now in Paul to Timothy. But now,

00:08:20.224 --> 00:08:23.616
Let's look at the other side and for that

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:27.744
I turn the page back to reading one, which is from 1984 to 1985.

00:08:27.744 --> 00:08:30.656
The fiery prophet Amos.

00:08:30.656 --> 00:08:33.184
Amos is one of the greatest of the

00:08:33.344 --> 00:08:37.920
Minor prophets, just means that his book is short of those of the major prophets.

00:08:37.664 --> 00:08:43.136
But Amos was often cited by the leaders of our civil rights movement in the mid-20th century.

00:08:43.040 --> 00:08:46.208
Because Amos is one of the great voices for the church.

00:08:46.144 --> 00:08:47.936
Social justice.

00:08:47.936 --> 00:08:50.496
Voice on behalf of the poor.

00:08:50.304 --> 00:08:53.600
Listen now, a voice raised to the

00:08:53.376 --> 00:08:55.136
In opposition.

00:08:55.008 --> 00:08:57.344
To the abuse of authority

00:08:57.472 --> 00:09:03.776
Now, having said all these positive things about political authority, not wishing to gainsay any of it,

00:09:04.096 --> 00:09:06.528
I also want to echo

00:09:06.688 --> 00:09:08.480
The prophet Amos.

00:09:08.480 --> 00:09:10.752
Now listen as he speaks

00:09:12.448 --> 00:09:13.920
Hear this

00:09:14.528 --> 00:09:17.568
You who trample upon the needy

00:09:18.368 --> 00:09:20.800
And destroy the poor of the land.

00:09:21.888 --> 00:09:24.320
When will the new moon be over? you ask.

00:09:24.416 --> 00:09:29.088
That we may sell our grain and the Sabbath, that we may display the wheat. Amen.

00:09:29.536 --> 00:09:32.352
Okay, the first part of it is clear enough.

00:09:33.312 --> 00:09:35.168
You in authority.

00:09:35.936 --> 00:09:45.984
who trample upon the needy. In other words, you're not securing their dignity. You're not securing tranquility for them. You're using your power

00:09:45.504 --> 00:09:47.680
hour to trample upon them.

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:50.496
And to destroy the poor of the land.

00:09:50.496 --> 00:09:52.512
Not to lift them up

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:57.728
Let's say through a properly managed economy that gives people the opportunity.

00:09:57.856 --> 00:09:58.656
you know,

00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:01.184
To to move out of their poverty

00:10:01.248 --> 00:10:04.992
You're not lifting them up. You're trampling down the poor.

00:10:04.608 --> 00:10:14.656
Now, are there political authorities that do this? Yes. Up and down the ages, we can see them. We can see them around us today. And the church raises a prophetic word.

00:10:14.176 --> 00:10:15.328
Eddig voice, 198

00:10:15.616 --> 00:10:16.960
against them.

00:10:17.152 --> 00:10:22.400
Now, the second part is a little more puzzling to us, but it's making an important point.

00:10:22.752 --> 00:10:28.448
"'When will the new moon be over, you ask, "'that we may sell our grain and the Sabbath, "'that we may display the wheat?'

00:10:28.192 --> 00:10:38.048
what they're saying there is during times of these formal religious ceremonies and these certain times of the year they were not allowed to do business.

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:45.184
I can't wait for this religion thing to be over so I can get back to my work of exploitation. That's what he's saying.

00:10:45.344 --> 00:10:47.872
Notice in 1 Timothy,

00:10:47.968 --> 00:10:54.496
One of the purposes of a well-organized government is to provide for the flourishing of religion.

00:10:54.784 --> 00:10:58.336
But now here's people in power who are saying, "Ah, religion."

00:10:58.176 --> 00:11:01.952
Religion is just getting in the way of my exploitation.

00:11:01.792 --> 00:11:04.160
You can't wait for these services to be over.

00:11:05.120 --> 00:11:06.208
That's a

00:11:06.048 --> 00:11:08.480
Profound perversion

00:11:08.576 --> 00:11:12.128
Of the purpose of government, of power.

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:14.208
Listen to this now.

00:11:14.528 --> 00:11:16.960
He imagines these sort of wealthy

00:11:17.696 --> 00:11:19.424
Powerful figure saying

00:11:19.456 --> 00:11:24.736
We will diminish the ephah, add to the shekel, and fix our scales for cheating.

00:11:24.768 --> 00:11:26.304
Well, what's that?

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:26.912
But,

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:33.824
So economic exploitation. So we're talking about weighing things and measuring things and, you know, what's this cost and, you know,

00:11:33.664 --> 00:11:35.840
Instead of doing it fairly, it's

00:11:36.032 --> 00:11:46.080
No, I'm going to fix the system. I'm going to game the system to get what I want. Now, in ancient times, it was all kind of crude, just a matter of, you know, how you measure it.

00:11:45.600 --> 00:11:46.688
measuring things.

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:48.768
Is it being done today?

00:11:49.248 --> 00:11:54.784
Yeah, just in a much more sophisticated manner and probably a somewhat more hidden manner.

00:11:55.872 --> 00:12:00.352
Are there people today economically who are gaming the system?

00:12:00.192 --> 00:12:02.112
For their own advantage?

00:12:03.008 --> 00:12:04.960
Indifferent to the poor?

00:12:05.536 --> 00:12:09.504
In fact, using the poor to get ahead themselves

00:12:09.248 --> 00:12:10.432
Yeah, sure.

00:12:11.104 --> 00:12:14.560
What's the purpose, everybody, of economic power?

00:12:15.360 --> 00:12:18.656
Not just to aggrandize my own, you know, position.

00:12:18.912 --> 00:12:22.848
But to use my economic power to lift others up

00:12:22.848 --> 00:12:25.216
See, and there's Catholic social teaching, right?

00:12:24.928 --> 00:12:29.408
Catholic social teaching affirms the market economy. Doesn't like socialism.

00:12:29.152 --> 00:12:33.664
or socialist forums. It likes the market economy for all kinds of reasons.

00:12:33.536 --> 00:12:35.008
but but

00:12:34.848 --> 00:12:36.096
It wants...

00:12:35.904 --> 00:12:42.752
More and more people involved in the market economy so they can participate in it in a way that lifts them up.

00:12:42.784 --> 00:12:50.368
So it likes investment that's not just for the advantage of the investor, but investment that is

00:12:50.272 --> 00:12:55.232
Lifts others up and provides more opportunities and jobs and so on.

00:12:56.192 --> 00:13:03.040
How do we think about our economic lives? How do we think about the power that some of us wield economically?

00:13:02.944 --> 00:13:03.776
Just, just.

00:13:03.648 --> 00:13:05.344
Make me richer.

00:13:05.088 --> 00:13:07.712
No, no. The focus should be on

00:13:07.744 --> 00:13:11.584
And indeed, don't the popes tell us this in the Catholic social teaching?

00:13:12.352 --> 00:13:17.408
Once the demands of necessity and propriety have been met in your own life,

00:13:17.312 --> 00:13:19.424
Everything else you own.

00:13:19.360 --> 00:13:21.280
For longs to the poor.

00:13:21.056 --> 00:13:22.976
That's Leo the 13th

00:13:22.720 --> 00:13:25.824
the founder of the modern Catholic social teaching tradition

00:13:26.720 --> 00:13:29.152
That's a hard saying.

00:13:29.472 --> 00:13:31.552
That's a hard saying everybody

00:13:31.552 --> 00:13:34.272
How are we using our economic power?

00:13:34.432 --> 00:13:36.288
As well as our political power

00:13:37.344 --> 00:13:39.648
See, Catholic social teaching

00:13:39.904 --> 00:13:41.760
It doesn't demonize power.

00:13:41.696 --> 00:13:46.432
It doesn't demonize economic power or economic opportunity. Right.

00:13:47.168 --> 00:13:51.360
But it wants to make sure that both political power and economic power

00:13:52.288 --> 00:13:53.760
Our animated

00:13:53.632 --> 00:13:54.912
And finally, finally, finally,

00:13:54.688 --> 00:13:55.872
By love.

00:13:57.472 --> 00:13:59.712
So that my power is used

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:01.536
For the good of the other,

00:14:02.848 --> 00:14:04.704
Now, I'll close with this.

00:14:04.672 --> 00:14:07.360
in God what come together

00:14:07.392 --> 00:14:10.112
Precisely power and love.

00:14:10.944 --> 00:14:16.224
Is God all powerful? Yes, over all things. Nothing limits God's capacity.

00:14:17.088 --> 00:14:20.768
But his power is identical to his love

00:14:21.728 --> 00:14:23.168
Now we found it.

00:14:23.392 --> 00:14:26.496
Now we found the key to Catholic social teaching.

00:14:26.752 --> 00:14:29.920
May the power you legitimately exercise

00:14:30.144 --> 00:14:32.896
They'll always be animated by love.

00:14:33.632 --> 00:14:34.848
And God bless you.

00:14:37.664 --> 00:14:41.856
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

00:14:41.632 --> 00:14:47.232
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire dot Org.
